metadata.title: Call them by their format: the specification of academic publication.

blocks.text: As we have seen, the making of formats is not a mono causal or teleological process, or a linear succession of improvements towards an ultimate form of academic communication. It is rather the outcome of various and heterogeneous processes, to which any kind of deterministic approach, whether “hard” or “soft” should be alien if looking at the complexity and versatility of these shared textual features. If we extend Siles’s reflections about the “blog”, formats are the outcome of a dynamic stabilization process, happening through the dialog of writing practices, technological development and the circulation of discursive elements. In this way, and through time, shared and stable representations about what this format is, does and allows crystallise.. It is a process by which writing and reading practices get anchored in specific requirements and expectations, no matter the contentIt is a process independent from the type of content it supports, and in which writing practices get rooted prior to any first kind of mediation. Formats operate when they inhabit individual and collective practices, acting as a “horizon of expectations” for writing and reading. After having described how format come to play within the scholarly worlds, we would like to to look closer at this horizon and its effect towards scholarly activities and communities.
How do scholarly formats organise worlds?  from names to infrastructures, institutions, and frames

After having shown how formats are ”made”, we want to understand what formats do. We would like to argue that their action revolves around three distinct axes of scholarly organizations: the technical one, acting as infrastructure, the social, acting as institution,  and the epistemological one, acting as frame.

Formats act as technological infrastructures since the material features they prescript condition the technical organizations and protocols needed to setup their instantiation. Infrastructures are the basic framework on which systems are built. Formats definitions structure storage and transportation facilities. Combined with communication protocols, they compose regimes of circulation and production for the social and economic actors involved in scholarly communication.

Formats also act as social institutions, as they produce recognition among actors that and as an outcome a kind of social organization. The rise of the journal des sçavans in the XVIIIth century was motivated by the project of providing a global “echo chamber” to the latest discoveries in the domain of sciences and humanities. This project quickly called for new modes of organization, new tools for its consultation, and installed progressively a new regime of scholarly discourse leading to a shift from private correspondences to community-oriented publications. Even if detached from a specific academy or learned society, the journal des sçavans endorsed various institutional responsibilities towards scholarly worlds, such as evaluation, preservation and distribution of texts. These were traditionally handled by other actors such as publishers or states. It was therefore a “paper institution”. A similar situation could be described around University Presses and the specific setup they deployed around the institution of scholarly book from the XIXth century.

Lastly, formats act as an epistemological frame, because, as a genre of writing associated with certain typographic and literary features, they define a certain way to perform authenticity within scholarly arguments. Formats are partly made by the way they display common typographic and organizational features between main texts and the textuality they are inscribed too, what Genette call peritext. In Footnote: a curious history, Anthony Grafton showed how interpersonal exchanges of authors could dramatically set the standards and expectations of a disciplinary community. Grafton has shown how debates and evolutions within the history discipline have been the theater of an epistemological debate about the role of evidence on the one hand, and narrativity of history on the other hand. The normalization of the footnote as one of the indispensable typographical features allowing to describe a text as an “history book” was the outcome of an acre debate in which were conflicted two different regimes of authenticity, literary one and documentary one, for which footnote turned to be as much the theatre of dispute as the instrument of its resolution through its stabilization and progressively shared use. In a similar and more contemporary register, knowledge sociologists such as Pontille have shown that “writing formats”, in the discipline of sociology, were a strong marker for the distinction of several distinct scientific worlds within the same academic discipline, rhetorical elements such as plan or use of personal pronouns instaured a two-pole space between an “hermeneutic regime” attached to literary and narrative on the one hand, and an “experimental regime” attached to a certain ideality of meaning and tending to a certain textual transparency. Focusing on explicitly named formats such as IMRAD, these works show that formats act as gatherers for disparate scholars recognizing themselves as respecting the same regime of authenticity, while they act in the same time as the instantiation of boundaries around a self-recognizing professional community.

As much as we have demonstrated previously that formats emergence were the outcome of remediations and modelling processes inspired by extraneous genres and media practices, scholarly formats practice happens within a “bow net of discourses” about knowledge in which reading and writing practices are influenced by intricated interpretational frames. In the last part of this chapter we will now focus on a contemporary case study for understanding the action of scholarly formats towards contemporary practices and communities.
How does the play with scholarly formats make scholarly worlds specifications ? the case of An Inquiry Into Modes Of Existence

Several initiatives at the center and periphery of the academy have experimented with the capacity of formats to displace and provoke knowledge experiments within scholarly collectives. Whether it be through the remediation of formats at the borders of different worlds such as the Pamphlet, reinvestments of the role and shape of scholarly journals or crafted innovation about contemporary printed scholarly book forms, these experiments actively work with formats while considering them as actors of knowledge production. Among these experiments stands the project An Inquiry into Modes of Existence (AIME), that the authors of this paper happened to participate to or to observe from a participant observation perspective. We propose to focus on this first-hand experience to report the consequences of contemporary plays with scholarly formats in the light of the format’s agency reported in the previous section.

The AIME project is a philosophical investigation aimed at learning “how to compose a common world” by transforming a text written by Bruno Latour into a collective inquiry dealing with ontological pluralism. For that purpose, the AIME team has developed a complex setup aimed at fostering various interpretational practices towards the Inquiry’s theoretical frame and empirical sites of reflection. This setup was also aimed at acting as a social cornerstone for involving some of the reader in the evolution of the project’s documentation, reframing them then as co-inquirers. To do so, the project was embodied in instances as different as a printed document, a website hosting at least 3 different interfaces, and a various set of workshops, exhibitions and  experiments.

The systematic review of the diversity of feedbacks describing and critiquing the organizational and material setup of the AIME project, shows that project’s format names have played a crucial roles in the phenomena of alignment and displacement, reinforcement and critique, gathering and antagonizing, of the project. To demonstrate and precise that hypothesis, we have spotted the different names used to describe project’s setup within the discursive traces surrounding the setup and its direct experiences - what one could call project’s epitext - and analysed them in regard to the effects these names produced on project’s performance. We are going to focus on three of the most used formats : a “philosophy book”, a “blog”, and an “encyclopedia”. While the two first names have been used by the authorial team of the project, whether directly (“philosophy book”) or as an oppositional figure used for describing what it was not (“blog”), the last one was spotted within the written reviews and discussions of the project. The review of the causes and effects of these three particular names on the practices and collectives surrounding AIME will hopefully help to refine our comprehension of the agency of formats on scholarly communication  .

AIME is a “philosophy book”, as it was published by recognized editors (Harvard University Press and La Découverte for the respective english and french versions for instance), presents “philosophical contents”, and is called as such on AIME’s website. However, the “book” section points to an interactive space which does not fit with the experience of a book, whether it would be print or even electronic ; the print instance, on its side, kind of lacks or betrays what one could expect from the format of a scholarly book, as features such as footnotes and references are not presented on it, because they are deported on the digital instance.

AIME is a “blog”. This name was staged in several ways : as an oppositional stance about the way co-inquirers contributions were specified in their roles (contribute to content rather than comment or discuss) and form, as a comparison anchor for assessing the features of the project as more or less innovative,  and eventually as an actual part of the vast setup of the project (AIME’s official blog).

AIME is an “encyclopedia”. It was called as such at several occasions, while this appellation was never used within team’s vocabulary. The interesting thing about this appending is that, when looking at these mentions, they are rooted in several levels to the content and materiality of the project : some infer the naming of AIME as an encyclopedia from the systematic nature of Bruno Latour’s inquiry ; some attach the presence of vocabulary entries to the entries of an encyclopedia ; interestingly, old and new formats of the encyclopedia collide in this movement of association as the collective nature of AIME has called to its association to “Wikipedia” (that is, in fact, the Wiki format), and therefore by association the idea and presupposed specification of an encyclopedia. This presupposition provoked claims and critiques, for instance about the absence of some topics from the book. As a result, the project went appropriated by communities of users surrounding the wiki.

When comparing AIME feedbacks to the formats’ actions exposed in the previous section as an infrastructuring, institutionalizing and framing processes, one can see that the institutionalizing goal of AIME’s formats has been dramatically discussed thanks to its collective-aimed design, and the recurrent parallels made - willingly or not - with contemporary formats characterized by a multiplicity of actors and the blurriness of separation between readers and writers, such as the blogs or collaborative encyclopedias. However, as an idiosyncratic project not primarily aimed at being repurposed for other contents and inquiries, the technically infrastructuring action of this format remained absent. Eventually, the epistemic framing effect of format was proven to play its full role regarding the legitimation of the “philosophic” and even “scholarly” qualities of the arguments advanced through the setup.

All the claims related to project’s various names show the action of formats towards the project: through a series of displacements and comparisons, the project got understood, interpreted and used in a variety of ways.  These displacements have challenged the project’s intrinsic dynamic (as planned) as well as the formats it has been referred to. The inquiry about the AIME project also calls for a more precise account on the role of formats according to contents and meaning: several formats can live in the same setup, and this multiplicity how formats are as well an affair of species than anatomy.
How to provoke knowledge production through the specification of scholarly formats ? multiplication, translation, reconfiguration

As demonstrated in this chapter, the continuously changing relation between discursive and material practices associated with academic communication conducts scholarly formats to be agents of normalization that set shared “horizons of expectations” for texts, as much as they are at the same time the outcome of a continuous betrayal of the pacts they carry, importing - deliberately or not - extraneous frames for interpreting and producing the textual forms they are embodied by. This paradoxical relation to the laws of scholarly communication may be enlightened by a closer look to the relation of formats to normativity. When used in a context of design and planification for the production of textual forms, formats are indeed the name of a prescription. They define a priori the need for specific production setups, transportation & storage facilities, display setups in libraries and bookstores, intended markets and targeted audiences, and even scenarii of use and day-by-day practices.

However this prescription never directly preempt contents, meaning or experiences. It is a conditional prescription which “sets conditions” rather than “give instructions”, and this explains why when inspected in the context of a sociology of textual uses, however, formats are also normative agents in the sense that they produce a posteriori a conventional frame for the interpretation of texts and the formation of publics, which can never be totally put under the control of the prescriptive choices associated with formats. There is therefore a dynamicity of formats,  as this normativity a posteriori retroactively operates on the normativity to be imposed to formats to come. Because of its dynamic qualities, the law instaured by formats always contains from the very time of its formulation the conditions of their own transgression, its intrinsic “principle of contamination”, as coined by Derrida about the paradoxes of genre classification. Therefore the instantiation of formats normativity is as well the registration of a jurisprudence as the application of a doctrine, as confirms Michel Serres’ definition of format as “the making of a law from repetition”.

The two-fold dynamics that makes formats and their action on scholarly worlds may be usefully reframed through the notion of specification. Within the field of biology, specification describes at the same time how a species gets discriminated from a broader genre, and how an individual gets determined and described through - non-exclusive - properties. This chapter has shown how scholarly formats are both the outcome of a specification process by which socio-cultural and technical processes stabilize material-discursive forms, and the agents of the specification of scholarly production, reading and writing processes, as they instaure frames, institutions and infrastructures for these practices. Therefore, naming the format of a document is a performative operation which connects material and formal specificities with discursive practices in a co-dependent way, as it instantiates the specifications embedded in that name at the same time it constitutes them through their specific and local instantiations.

In the field of design and computer science, specification also refers to the prescription of features and qualities expected from a material setup while it is still in the state of a project. According to the third sense - specification as prescription - making formats is also a deliberate and constitutive act for the formation of scholarly worlds.  If one acknowledges that the specification operated by formats is performative and contributes on its own terms to knowledge production, researching with scholarly formats turns to be a critical and genuinely scholarly endeavour. For instance, calling “scholarly book” a textual instance which does not correlates with what one thinks of scholarly books is an act of specification in three ways: (1) it suggests to read what’s attached to this name as a scholarly book - whatever the “instruction manual” embedded in that name would read for different individuals, based on their experience and mindset. (2) it adds a supplementary trait to a specific text as something which is, among other things, a scholarly book, and thus attach this specific text to a broader group, calling for intertextual interpretation. (3) it distinguishes this instance as a “scholarly book” from other texts that belong to a different category like, say, “literature books” or “books” in general. This operation reconfigures boundaries and territories between these different formats, and questions specific features and values that make the “horizon of expectation” of this format among others. Each of these operations make the format of a specific “scholarly book” a constitutive and critical gesture towards what is a scholarly book. As formats orient as much as they can be oriented, contemporary experiments in scholarly formats are always a subtle equilibrium game between orientation and disorientation. This equilibrium is found through an appropriate level of displacement between discourse and materiality : developing too displaced material properties for a text makes the quest for a format’s name painful and disorienting and incidentally invites actors to sail to safer territories, while using scholarly formats without any attention to their agency provokes the risk of a formatted scholarly practice, where the overload of orientation tends to formalize intellectual work by reducing it to the recognition of certain formal features validating authenticity and guiding the production of knowledge. In order to play the formats game in proper ways, let’s end this chapter by proposing three different strategies towards the use of scholarly formats within academic research :
multiply formats for the reworking of arguments within a same project, conscious of their capacity to articulate collectives and alternative interpretations
translate emerging and/or alien formats to the specifications of scholarly work, conscious of their capacity to import embedded practices, representations and collectives

reconfigure formats, which means to use the power of conventions and representations carried by the recognition of formats while staying attentive to the situated and individual specifications of each scholarly project

metadata.title: Chapitre 1

blocks.text: “Academic journal”, “monograph”, “conference proceedings”  are just few names that are able to evoke common representations about the values and practices attached to the rich tradition of academic work.“Academic journal”, “monograph”, “conference proceedings”  are just few names that are able to open up to common and shared objectrepresentations ofabout the academic world.  They evoke values and practices attached to long and rich traditions. They recall precise frameworks of thinking, reading and writing -- connecting together the representations of specific institutions, infrastructures and activities. However, if we compare these representationsthem with the contemporary features of such objects they relate to a certain cognitive dissonance may arise. Is an “academic journal” still a “journal” when it is less and less affected by its periodicity, and more and more sold and consumed through articles rather than issues? Are “conference proceedings” still relevant when the term stands for the online publication audio or video recordings? What is an “academic book” when this term increasingly designates various objects, spanning from collections of diverse fragments and excerpts found on the web to .epub compositions. For not leaving aside “near print” objects often presented in .pdf files, or the old printed objects that we continue to store in our bookshelves and carry in our bags ? Apparently their names are more stable and solid than what they call for.

While under the umbrella of traditional names we can find a growing collection of variegated objects, we can acknowledge new names act as ambiguous connectors between the “old” and the “new”: “academic blog”, “augmented book”, “thematic research collections”, “digital critical editions”. In each of these expressions, an old name gets paired with a new one, as if this combination was needed to bridge a gap. All of these names seem to provide a scholarly flavour to very different practices and regimes of knowledge across individuals and communities. They carry expectations about  authors, audiences, textual genres,organizations, conditions of (re)production, periodicity and circuits of circulation. Yet, they do not rely on a precise nor fixed set of material instances. Let’s call “academic formats” these names and their articulation with the social and cultural assemblages they are attached to.

The word “format” may at least underpin three different meanings, spanning from a more descriptive sense to a more normative one. For example, when it is used to describe printed objects, “formats” designate the “shape, size, and general makeup” of texts. Consequently they are associated with specific conditions of production (i.e. a “hard cover book”, which relate to specific book-making techniques) and use (i.e. a “pocket book”, which suggests what kind of situations this format is purposed for). In other situations the term designates specific genres of texts. These are “socially recognized, repeated strateg[ies] for achieving similar goals in situations socially perceived as being similar” or more precisely regarding texts, “mode[s] of recognition instantiated in discourse”. This process of recognizing formats as genre is grounded  on material and rhetorical features such as textual organization and critical apparatus design. More recently, when the term is used in  digital related environments , the term designates “a set of rules according to which a technology can operate”. These rules affect both the algorithmic process and the user experience associated with a particular media or content type. Physical features conditioning production and use; recognition process embedding supposedly shared but implicit goals; set of rules for the future performance of media: in all of these intricated definitions, formats are the name of an articulation between  “material-discursive practices” and a certain regime of virtuality, which makes formats present in parallel to their actualization in specific texts   .

How to qualify the presence of formats within scholarly texts, practices and communities? Isn’t the stubborn survivance of old format names, as such or through their recombination with new terms, the sign of an agency of formats - their ability to influence or operate on the scholarly world beyond representation?  how does the name of an academic format arises and get used and attached to specific practices and conventions? how do these associations evolve over time? and, if it does not only represent a certain set of things,  what does this name make within the academic world? To explore these questions we will first draw back from a historic perspective how do formats emerge and stabilize as recognized forms of texts (1). Then we will inspect their agencyactions from a technical, social and epistemological perspective (2). We will finally focus on a recent case of experiment with scholarly formats in which authors have been involved: the philosophy project An Inquiry Into Modes of Existence, from which we will try to understand how scholarly formats design can contribute to knowledge production and academic organization.
How do scholarly formats make their names ? techno-social, editorial processes

By drawing upon  the history of academic outlets we can derive some elements helpful to grasp how formats have been “made” in the past. We aim to obtain a better understanding of the process by which textual features come to be stabilized enough that their name produces a shared horizon for reading, writing and other practices of texts.

Technological innovations can induce new ways of producing and replicating texts, driving change within the social groups and organizations associated with these texts. The Middle-Age format of the monastery book spread as a consequence to the popularization of the codex and its related book-making techniques. Then, the apparition of the moveable type in the late XVth century and the related “Guttenberg revolution” caused dramatic changes in modes of circulation and production of print forms. Furthermore it also asked for more accurate books reproductions and therefore for the creation of identical copies for books. Somehow it is thank to the increasing industrialization of the printing processes, that the scholarly book format acquired a recognized shapes and forms associated with particular types of books.

Technological innovation may also cause the disappearance of some formats under the action of  different processes: obsolescence, such as the progressive disparition of manuscript copies in favor of print publications; complication, where new technological systems complicate previous practices and types of texts. This latter process is particularly interesting, for example, the apparition of the print caused the disparition of glosed bibles which were a very spread format across the Middle Age, but hardly reproducible through the first print setups. After the period of incunables which followed shortly the invention of the moveable type, a lot of typographic features and centuries-long crafted typographic apparatuses were wiped out of scholarly book features, such as the role of inline images as markers for the organization of text. It is through a long recomposition of typographic elements adapted both to the scholarly practices of the time, and the new specifications brought by printing press technology, that the “scholarly book” regained the qualities we know it by, through a number of episodes of drawbacks and innovation - as testifies the alternative disparition and reapparition of parts titles and indexes in reedition of antique scholarly classics.

Scholarly formats also rise and die in function of  scholarly institutions and collectives. For example, the emergence of the University book during XIIth century is the outcome of the formation of the University institutions urging  to reinvent the book for a broader readership and for new pedagogical practices. First, these new conditions of use called for faster and cheaper ways to produce them: this need was answered by a new reproduction system called pecia was invented in which specific book instantiations were spread as untouched exemplar to be copied and shared. Consequently, this new system required for the “scholarly book” format features to evolve towards economic rationalization: the scholarly book’s pages were compacted and filled with more and more abbreviations taught at University. Secondly, the practices instituted by the University led to editorial design innovations turned toward related pedagogical practices. As scholarly documents of these periods progressively left their main role of content storage devices to be enrolled in growingly complex scenarii of use such as collective reading and comment of texts, their format started to thrive for silent reading instead of scripto continua with the invention of typographic space. Besides, their enrolment within disputes and comments asked for an instrumentation of the academic book formats,  which provoked improvements in the semantic markup of texts such as paragraphs, titles lists, or the organization of glosis.

Formats evolution may also be provoked by new cognitive tasks. The increase of knowledge production and storage systems is a recurring concern within scholarly communities history, and the impossibility for a single person to remember a growing corpus of academic works asked for new specifications for the design of books.  as instruments of non linear reading. A first instance of this process is the XIIIth century university book evolving to add to its specification diverse markup features aimed at supporting information research activities. Another instance is the emergence of the commonplace books, which appeared both as the outcome of this need for intellectual apparatus and the consolidation of a pedagogical practice of compilation characteristic of humanistic formation. The scholarly journal, before its contemporary instantiation as a format aimed at sharing highly specialized knowledge within a community of peers, was  the expression of a growing awareness about information overload. For example the Journal des Sçavans, one of the first academic journals created by Denis Sallo in 1665, was primarily constituted by books excerpts and resumés, aiming at giving to readers a broad overview of academic intellectual production. One century later, the same name was used to define extremely specialized publications addressing a very specific readerships. These two episodes depict two life of the “same” format, two opposite strategies to answer the same concern.

One last process for the making of formats comes from specific editorial requirementsis the editorial remediation. Scholars inspired from existing non-academic editorial forms for inventing new formats of communication adapted to their intellectual projects. The rise of the scholarly journal cannot be properly understood without being attentive to the rise of periodic publication in the XVIIIth century which acted as a strong model for the definition of the first editorial missions of this new form, not much without acknowledging the importance of correspondence practices which instaured in the learned societies of that era a certain sensibility to short written forms as ways of interacting with scholarly content. The seminal and idiosyncratic status of the Dictionnaire d’Histoire Critique of Pierre Bayle, on its side, was proven to have taken editorial inspiration from previous forms as different as antic compilations, and sacred texts commentaries. As these examples show, formats apparition is as much influenced by new conditions of production and social uses of texts, as it is by specific intellectual programs asking for the evolution and stabilization of new “horizons of expectations” for writing and reading scholarly texts.
